---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro"

let alternatives = [
  {
    "name": "BadgeAI",
    "url": "https://www.badgeai.org/",
    "pros": [
      "Nice looking badges",
      "Multi-lingual site",
      "Neutral / Non-Judgemental"
    ],
    "cons": [
      '<a href="https://www.badgeai.org/futur" target="_blank">Big vision</a>',
      "Not actively maintained"
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "TrueBadge",
    "url": "https://truebadge.ai",
    "pros": [],
    "cons": [
      "Account required",
      "Paid service",
      "Built for agencies and brands"
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "AI Honesty Badge",
    "url": "https://www.aihonestybadge.com",
    "pros": [
      "Simple",
      "One line of code"
    ],
    "cons": [
      "Hues suggest judgement"
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "Clear AI Register",
    "url": "https://clearairegister.com",
    "pros": [],
    "cons": [
      "Account required",
      "Per-site verification",
      "Passive judgement"
    ]
  },
]
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>The AI Trasparency Landscape</h1>
  <h2>Comparrison of the Alternatives</h2>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Alternative</th>
      <th>Notes</th>
    </tr>
    {
    alternatives.map((alt) => (
    <tr>
      <td><a href={alt.url} target="_blank">{alt.name}</a></td>
      <td>
        <ul class="pros">
          {
          alt.pros.map((pro) => (
          <li set:html={pro}></li>
          ))
          }
        </ul>
        <ul class="cons">
          {
          alt.cons.map((con) => (
          <li set:html={con}></li>
          ))
          }
        </ul>
      </td>
    </tr>
    ))
    }
  </table>
  <h2>EU AI Transparency Act</h2>

  <h2>Next Steps</h2>
  <p>This project proposes that along with the AI Transparency Badge, site authors and app developers would create a written declaration of AI usage (or non-usage) linked via their site or app with the intent of being expressive beyond the limitations of the Badge. See <a href="ai_declaration">this project's AI Declaration</a> as an example.</p>

  <p>You could also consider implementing <a href="https://aitxt.ing/">ai.txt</a> to help AI understand what you're offering online. Other standards exist, or are emerging (<a href="https://arxiv.org/html/2505.07834v1">ai.txt: A Domain-Specific Language for Guiding AI Interactions with the Internet</a> for example which may have a higher barrier to entry, <a href="https://llmstxt.org/">llms-txt</a>, and <a href="https://github.com/kaylacar/ai-txt">ai-txt on Github</a>) It's also worth checking out <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/robots.txt">the BBC's robots.txt</a> where they request LLMs not access large portions of their content for training, etc.</p>
</BaseLayout>
